          "text": "The old house at the foot of the hill was known in the neighborhood as the 'Japanese house.'\n\nIt had belonged to Kenji Tanaka, a colonial-era police official. Granite foundation stones, double-pane sliding doors. The tatami had been pulled out and ondol heating laid in, but the ceiling height and the angle of the corridors still carried the scent of another era. On liberation day, Tanaka disappeared to the docks with a single cloth bundle, and the house stood empty for a time before Victor's father, Cha Bong-su, bought it for a song.\n\nNo one asked why it was so cheap.\n\n─\n\nBong-su ran five small fishing boats. Officially: coastal fishing vessels. Unofficially: a nighttime route between the islands and the mainland. Sony transistor radios, Seiko electronic watches, National electric fans — things you couldn't find elsewhere. His boats left a small northern port at eleven at night and slipped quietly into a rocky cove below the cliff at four in the morning.\n\nOne night the waves were bad. A box of watches went under.\n\nThe rescued Seikos hung in rows on a laundry line in the attic. Drying out the salt. Young Victor loved climbing up to that attic. Dozens of watches hanging from the ceiling, each one ticking its own rhythm. They all pointed to different times.\n\n'Victor.'\n\nHis father called from the bottom of the attic stairs.\n\n'Those are all set to Japanese time. In our house, Japanese time runs.'\n\nHis father said it with a smile, but young Victor couldn't tell if it was a joke or the truth.\n\n─\n\nThe deliveries were Victor's job and his closest friend Seong-jun's.\n\nAt three o'clock, when school let out, the two retrieved their bicycles from the storeroom. Three or four milk cans were strapped to the cargo rack — 'Namyang Dairy' printed clearly on the outside, but inside: Seiko watches wrapped in cotton.\n\nCrossing the harbor bridge always made Victor's heart pound.\n\nTwo policemen stood at the entrance. But they paid no attention to two uniformed schoolboys on bicycles. Adults with handcarts sometimes got stopped, but Victor and Seong-jun pedaled through with guileless faces.\n\n'Seong-jun. Look straight ahead. Never dodge the officer's eyes.'\n\nVictor led the way. Seong-jun chewed his lip behind him.\n\n'You're more nervous than me. You've got more in your cans.'\n\n'Precisely why I walk more confidently.'\n\nSeong-jun didn't understand it — but somehow it seemed right.\n\n─\n\nThe street market was Victor's second school.\n\nBuilt from the debris of postwar American supply crates. Step inside the alley and smells collided — damp plywood, solvent, braised fish, and somewhere, American pop music leaking out.\n\nHo-ya Ajeossi always came running out first. Short, pot-bellied, perpetually in a sleeveless undershirt. He'd lost hearing in one ear during the war, they said — though he heard selectively. He always caught mentions of police. He never heard talk of taxes.\n\n'How many today?'\n\n'Thirty-two.'\n\n'Yesterday's sold out. Can you get waterproof ones? Customers keep asking.'\n\n'Ajeossi, would smuggled watches come with a waterproof specification sheet?'\n\nHo-ya laughed his rolling laugh and took the milk cans. His warehouse contained everything the world produced — film cameras, dress shirts, fountain pens, batteries, German binoculars. How they arrived, no one knew.\n\nThe tea room was their second stop.\n\nThe sign said 'Hong Tea Room,' but everyone called it Miss Hong's. Records always spinning. Madam Hong was in her forties, always in rouge and a skirt, her voice low and precise.\n\n'Victor's here. Seong-jun too.'\n\nShe always served them each a glass of citron tea. Victor liked that. She never charged them.\n\n'How many today, ma'am?'\n\n'Three. One for my wrist, one for my regulars, one for the back room.'\n\nMiss Hong's tea room was the information hub of the market. When the tax office would send inspectors. Which police precinct captain had been transferred. What ships had come into the docks — all of it drifted through those chairs. The Seiko watches were the subscription fee.\n\n─\n\nIn 1981, a workman renovating the house found a hidden wall in the basement.\n\nHe knocked — hollow. Victor's father broke it open himself. Inside: three wooden crates. The first held seventeen gold bars. The second held a bundle of deposit certificates. The third held celadon, a bronze Buddha, and scrolls wrapped in oiled paper.\n\nThings Kenji Tanaka had accumulated over thirty years.\n\nBong-su said nothing for three days. On the fourth morning, he called Victor and said quietly:\n\n'You need to know where this came from. And no one must ever know where it is now. Holding both of those things at once — that is what wealth is.'\n\nVictor was thirteen. He never forgot those words.\n\n─\n\nJune 2024. International Airport, Business Lounge.\n\nVictor was sixty. Completely gray. No watch on his wrist — since the day in his school years when he first unscrewed a Seiko from its strap, he had found an empty wrist more comfortable. Time isn't something you wear, he believed. It's something you read.\n\nOn the table: an envelope flown in from Seoul. A tax investigation pre-notice from the National Tax Service — transfer pricing inquiry into charter fee transactions between Yeongdo Shipping and its Singapore subsidiary. Opening date: July 1.\n\nHe didn't read it again. He already knew the contents. In fact, he had known for a long time that this day was coming. Yeongdo Shipping was the last Korean entity he had kept. Deliberately. The other seventeen had been wound down one by one over twenty years. He had kept Yeongdo Shipping alone because of the name — Yeongdo, the island where he grew up. If that was the only reason, you could call it sentimental, and he couldn't argue.\n\nOutside the window, the Dubai flight was separating from the jet bridge.\n\nA name stored in his phone: Ali Al-Mansouri. Dubai family office specialist. Victor had first met him in 2009, at a pre-conference for a Dubai world expo. Over the fifteen years since, the two men had done three projects together, abandoned two, and spent six months not speaking to each other once. The connection had held anyway.\n\nHe pressed the call button with his thumb. Three rings.\n\n'Ali. Time to wind down Yeongdo Shipping.'\n\nA brief silence. Then a low, precise voice.\n\n'I've been waiting for that call, Victor.'"
