          "text": "The Blue Moon was run by a neighborhood elder named Lee Tae-seok.\n\nNot a blood relation. Someone Victor had known since childhood in the port district. Tae-seok had always bought him meals. Ask him why, and he'd only say he owed Victor's father a debt. That was enough.\n\nBlue Moon was a six-room karaoke bar. Victor took over the floor management when Tae-seok was hospitalized for back surgery for two months.\n\nHe had one specific protocol.\n\nWhenever a new hostess arrived from Seoul, Victor would call Professor Oh first. The oldest regular. Giving him the first notification of new faces was Victor's form of deference. Professor Oh accepted it as natural. Victor understood that was simply how he operated.\n\n─\n\nThe incident happened in November 1989, during exam week.\n\nVictor had a textbook open in the back storeroom. The floor manager and two part-timers were handling the front. The bar opened at six. Usually quiet until eight.\n\nHe heard it at half past eight.\n\nGlass breaking. Then a woman screaming.\n\nVictor walked out with the ebony stick.\n\nHarder and heavier than steel — a practice bokken any martial artist would covet. Victor always brought it to Blue Moon. Heavy, but his hand knew it.\n\n─\n\nThe scene: four men standing in front of Professor Oh's table. Two hostesses had been pushed into the corner. One was covering her face. Professor Oh had stood to intervene and taken a punch to the nose. Blood spreading on a white shirt.\n\nThe apparent leader was shouting — demanding to see the new girl from Seoul. If she wasn't on the floor, where was she.\n\nVictor stood at the entrance and assessed the situation for two seconds.\n\nThen he walked in.\n\n─\n\nEbony sounds different.\n\nThe sound of hard ebony meeting bone — not light, not reversible. Two of the four went down in the first two strikes. One arm, one knee. The other two rushed him. Victor didn't step back. Something his trainer had taught him — in a tight space, step back and you die. Control the space first.\n\nLess than four minutes.\n\nAll four were on the floor. Nobody moved.\n\nVictor didn't put down the stick. He caught his breath and scanned the room. The two part-timers were pressed against the wall. Professor Oh was holding a handkerchief to his nose.\n\nVictor spoke.\n\n'Close the bar.'\n\n─\n\nOne phone call.\n\nA friend of Professor Oh — Sergeant Jang, Special Forces, on leave. Victor explained the situation. The sergeant asked two questions.\n\n'Did you run?'\n\n'Not yet.'\n\n'All four alive?'\n\n'Yes.'\n\n'Then this isn't a confession situation. Come now.'\n\n─\n\nVictor called Tae-seok, who was still in hospital.\n\n'Something happened at the bar. I need to be absent for a while.'\n\nTae-seok asked nothing.\n\n'Understood.'\n\nThat was all.\n\n─\n\nProfessor Oh aligned the staff's story.\n\nVictor was a customer nobody recognized. No one knew his name. He had fled first when the trouble started.\n\nBoth sides were injured. The police arrived; the perpetrators had no identification to show. The aggressors wanted their identities kept out. Professor Oh's side wanted a settlement. Blue Moon wanted to reopen.\n\nThe incident was quietly buried.\n\n─\n\nIn late November 1989, Victor was commissioned as a non-commissioned officer in the Special Forces.\n\nFive years of service began.\n\n─\n\nThe training was brutal. But the real training had already ended — in the port district. Physical tests, combat, demolitions basics — none of it broke him. In the Special Forces, Victor learned two new things: reading maps, and encrypted communications. Converting space into numbers. Compressing information into code. Those two skills would later be used in an entirely different way.\n\nThe sergeant asked one day:\n\n'Where did you learn to fight like that?'\n\n'The alleys.'\n\n'Does the port district have many dojos?'\n\n'Not dojos. Alleys.'\n\n─\n\nIn late 1994, Victor was discharged at the rank of staff sergeant.\n\nThe sergeant shook his hand. 'So what are you going to do now?'\n\nVictor said: 'Make a telephone do the work instead of me.'\n\nThe sergeant didn't know what that meant. He just laughed.\n\n─\n\nThat winter, Victor spent a month practically living in a Seoul electronics market.\n\nKorea was just beginning to see personal computers spread. IBM-compatible PCs, DOS operating systems, 9600-baud modems. A technician confirmed something: a computer could dial a phone number automatically.\n\nWhat he conceived was simple.\n\nThe computer reads a phone directory. Connects automatically. A recorded voice plays. If the line isn't cut, it takes an order.\n\nThe voice was a professional voice actor whose delivery resembled a popular TV personality of the time. Three actors. Victor wrote the scripts himself. Revised them endlessly. To prevent the call from being ended in the first second, you needed exactly one thing.\n\nCuriosity.\n\n'Hello, valued customer. We have selected you as one of our special prize winners. Confirm right now and receive your benefit.'\n\nPrize winner. Four words that made people stay on the line.\n\n─\n\nThe product started with water purifiers.\n\nBidets, air purifiers, massage chairs, bedding, kitchen goods. Half the department store price. No advertising costs, so margins were low. Low costs meant big discounts.\n\nConversion rate per call: 8%. Daily outbound calls: 2,000. Conversions: 160. Average order value: roughly $200.\n\nMonthly revenue: $1 million.\n\nFirst employees: three. Six months later: twenty-two.\n\n─\n\nVictor ran that business for three years.\n\nHe shifted from leasing equipment to manufacturing it. He bundled hardware and software into packages and sold them to franchisees in multiple cities. His own system became his own competition. He didn't mind. That was diffusion.\n\nThree-year total. At twenty-nine, Victor held cash and real estate worth approximately $1.1 million.\n\n─\n\nIn spring 1997, he wound the business down.\n\nHe passed it to a partner and converted the equipment to leases. A clean exit.\n\nAt the airport, he made a final call to Seong-jun.\n\n'Are you really going?'\n\n'Going.'\n\n'When will you come back?'\n\n'When it makes sense to.'\n\nA long silence. Then: 'Be careful.'\n\nDestination: America. Reason: the next stage. To learn how money crosses borders."
